Grammar configuration file (grammars)
-------------------------------------

Located at misc/syntax-ts/grammars, this file maps filenames and shebang
lines to grammar names.  The format is:

    file           <filename_regex>   <grammar_name> <display_name>
    shebang        <first_line_regex> <grammar_name> <display_name>
    inject         <parent_grammar>   <child_grammar> <node_type1>,...
    inject_dynamic <parent_grammar>   <block_node> <lang_node> <content_node>

The grammar_name is used to:
- Look up the grammar (via static registry or shared module loader).
- Load the query file <grammar_name>-highlights.scm from the queries/
  directory.

Example entries:

    file \.[ch]$ c C\ Program
    file \.py$ python Python\ Program
    shebang [/\x20]python[0-9.]* python Python\ Program
    inject markdown markdown_inline inline,pipe_table_cell
    inject html javascript script_element/raw_text
    inject_dynamic markdown fenced_code_block info_string code_fence_content

Important notes about regex syntax:
- MC's regex engine (mc_search with MC_SEARCH_T_REGEX) does NOT support
  \b (word boundary) or \s (whitespace class).
- Literal spaces in patterns are parsed as field separators, so they
  must be escaped as \x20 in the regex.
- Use [/\x20] instead of [\s/] for matching slash-or-space.

The file is read at runtime from ~/.local/share/mc/syntax-ts/grammars
(user path, checked first) or the system share directory.


Highlight query files (queries/*.scm)
--------------------------------------

Each grammar has a corresponding query file in misc/syntax-ts/queries/
named <grammar_name>-highlights.scm (e.g. c-highlights.scm,
python-highlights.scm, bash-highlights.scm).

Query files use the tree-sitter query syntax (S-expressions) to match
AST node patterns and assign capture names.  For example:

    (function_definition name: (identifier) @function)
    (string_literal) @string
    (comment) @comment
    [
      "if"
      "else"
      "return"
    ] @keyword

The capture names (the @name parts) are mapped to MC colors by the
ts_default_colors[] table in syntax.c.

Critical constraint: every node name and anonymous string literal in the
query file MUST exist in the grammar's symbol table (ts_symbol_names[]
in parser.c).  If any name is invalid, ts_query_new() returns NULL and
the entire query fails silently, causing fallback to legacy highlighting.

Query files support hierarchical capture names (e.g. @keyword.control,
@string.special).  The color lookup performs longest-prefix matching, so
@keyword.control is tried first, then @keyword.


Color mapping
-------------

The ts_default_colors[] table in syntax.c maps capture names to MC
foreground colors.  The colors are chosen to match MC's default syntax
highlighting appearance (blue background skin):

    Capture             Foreground Color    Purpose
    -------             ----------------    -------
    keyword             yellow              Language keywords
    keyword.other       white               Secondary keywords
    keyword.control     brightmagenta       Control flow (PHP)
    keyword.directive   magenta             Directives (Make)
    function            brightcyan          Function names
    function.special    brightred           Preprocessor macros
    function.builtin    brown               Built-in functions (Go)
    function.macro      brightmagenta       Macro invocations (Rust)
    type                yellow              Type names
    type.builtin        brightgreen         Built-in types (Go)
    string              green               String literals
    string.special      brightgreen         Char literals, escapes
    number              lightgray           Numeric literals
    number.builtin      brightgreen         Special numbers (Haskell)
    comment             brown               Comments
    comment.error       red                 CSS hex colors
    constant            lightgray           Constants
    constant.builtin    brightmagenta       Built-in constants
    variable            (default)           Variables
    variable.builtin    brightred           self, $vars
    variable.special    brightgreen         Shell expansions
    operator            brightcyan          Operators
    operator.word       yellow              Word-like operators
    delimiter           brightcyan          Brackets, punctuation
    delimiter.special   brightmagenta       Semicolons, bitwise ops
    property            brightcyan          Object properties
    property.key        yellow              Config file keys
    label               cyan                Labels
    tag                 brightcyan          HTML/XML tags
    markup.addition     brightgreen         Diff additions
    markup.deletion     brightred           Diff deletions
    markup.heading      brightmagenta       Diff headers

To change a color for all languages, edit the ts_default_colors[] table.
To change a color for a specific language, use a more specific capture
name in the query file (e.g. @keyword.control instead of @keyword) and
add a corresponding entry to the table.


Adding a new language
---------------------

To add tree-sitter highlighting for a new language:

1. Add the grammar to the download script.

   Edit src/editor/ts-grammars/download-grammars.sh and add a download
   entry pinned to a specific commit SHA:

       download <name> <github_org> <repo> <commit_sha>

   For grammars with non-standard layouts, specify the src prefix:

       download <name> <org> <repo> <sha> <src_prefix>

   If the grammar needs extra headers, use download_extra().  For
   GitLab-hosted grammars, use download_gitlab().

2. Register the grammar for static mode.

   Edit src/editor/ts-grammars/ts-grammar-registry.h:
   - Add an #ifdef HAVE_GRAMMAR_<UPPER> guarded extern declaration:
     #ifdef HAVE_GRAMMAR_<UPPER>
     extern const TSLanguage *tree_sitter_<name>(void);
     #endif
   - Add a similarly guarded entry to the ts_grammar_registry[] array:
     #ifdef HAVE_GRAMMAR_<UPPER>
     { "<name>", tree_sitter_<name> },
     #endif

   For shared mode, no registration is needed -- the grammar is
   discovered automatically from its .so file.  If the function name
   does not follow the tree_sitter_<name> convention, add an override
   to the ts_grammar_symbol_overrides[] table in ts-grammar-loader.h.

   The <name> must exactly match the function name suffix exported by
   the grammar's parser.c.  Some grammars use different names than their
   directory (e.g. the lisp/ directory exports tree_sitter_commonlisp,
   and cobol exports tree_sitter_COBOL).

3. Add the grammar to the build.

   Edit configure.ac (in the tree-sitter section):
   - Add <name> to all_ts_grammars.
   - If there is a scanner.c, add <name> to ts_scanner_c.
   - If there is a scanner.cc, add <name> to ts_scanner_cc.

4. Create a highlight query file.

   Create misc/syntax-ts/queries/<name>-highlights.scm with tree-sitter
   query patterns.  Use the grammar's node-types.json or the
   ts_symbol_names[] array in parser.c to find valid node names.

   You can also reference the upstream grammar repository's queries/
   directory for inspiration, but those queries often use capture names
   that don't match MC's color scheme and may reference nodes from
   different grammar versions.

   Test the query by extracting all node names used in the query and
   verifying they exist in the grammar's ts_symbol_names[] (see the
   "Validating query files" section).

5. Add the grammar mapping.

   Edit misc/syntax-ts/grammars and add file and/or shebang lines:
     file \.<ext>$ <name> Display\ Name
     shebang [/\x20]<interpreter> <name> Display\ Name

6. Update the installation rules.

   Edit misc/syntax-ts/Makefile.am and add <name>-highlights.scm to the
   TS_QUERYFILES list.

7. Rebuild.

   Run autoreconf (or autogen.sh) to regenerate the build system, then
   configure with --with-tree-sitter and build.  Run the unit tests:

       make check -C tests/src/editor

   The edit_syntax_ts test validates all query files against their
   grammars.


Removing or disabling a language
--------------------------------

To exclude a grammar at build time (without modifying any files):
- Use --with-tree-sitter-grammars=LIST to specify only the grammars
  you want.  Unselected grammars are not compiled, downloaded, or
  registered.

In shared mode, grammars can also be excluded at install time by simply
not installing the corresponding .so file and .scm query file.

To disable a grammar without removing its files:
- Comment out or remove its lines from misc/syntax-ts/grammars.
  The grammar will still be compiled but never matched at runtime.

To fully remove a grammar:
1. Remove its lines from misc/syntax-ts/grammars.
2. Remove its #ifdef-guarded entries from ts-grammar-registry.h.
3. Remove it from all_ts_grammars (and ts_scanner_c/ts_scanner_cc
   if applicable) in configure.ac.
4. Remove its download entry from download-grammars.sh.
5. Delete misc/syntax-ts/queries/<name>-highlights.scm.
6. Remove <name>-highlights.scm from TS_QUERYFILES in
   misc/syntax-ts/Makefile.am.


Updating a grammar
------------------

To update a grammar to a newer version:

1. Update the commit SHA in download-grammars.sh and re-download:

       make -C src/editor/ts-grammars download-grammars

   This will replace the grammar files in src/editor/ts-grammars/<name>/.

2. Check for ABI compatibility.  The grammars were generated by
   different tree-sitter versions (ranging from pre-0.22 to 0.25.x).
   The compatibility headers in src/editor/ts-grammars/tree_sitter/
   include patches for:
   - TSFieldMapSlice typedef (old grammars use this, new use TSMapSlice)
   - version/abi_version union in TSLanguage struct
   - Variadic REDUCE macro (old grammars use 2 positional args, new use
     4 named args)

   If the new grammar uses a newer ABI than 15 (TREE_SITTER_LANGUAGE_VERSION),
   you may need to update the system libtree-sitter.

3. Validate the query file against the new grammar.  Node names may have
   changed between versions.  See "Validating query files" below.

4. Rebuild and test:

       make -j$(nproc)
       make check -C tests/src/editor


Validating query files
----------------------

A query file must only reference node names that exist in the grammar.
If any node name is invalid, tree-sitter silently rejects the entire
query and the language falls back to legacy highlighting.

To extract the valid node names from a grammar:

    grep -oP '"[^"]*"' src/editor/ts-grammars/<name>/parser.c \
        | sort -u

Specifically, look at the ts_symbol_names[] array in parser.c for the
authoritative list.  Also check ts_field_names[] for valid field names.

To extract node names used in a query file:

    1. Strip ;; comments and #match?/#not-match? predicate lines.
    2. Extract all bare identifiers (node names) and quoted strings
       (anonymous nodes like "if", "return").
    3. Ignore _ which is the tree-sitter wildcard.
    4. Check each against the grammar's symbol table.

The unit test (tests/src/editor/edit_syntax_ts.c) validates all query
files by compiling them with ts_query_new() against their respective
grammars.  Run it with:

    make check -C tests/src/editor

If you find invalid nodes, either remove the offending patterns from the
query file or replace them with valid node names from the grammar.


Troubleshooting
---------------

Tree-sitter highlighting does not appear:

    The most common cause is a query compilation failure.  If any node
    name or anonymous literal in the .scm file does not exist in the
    grammar, the entire query is silently rejected and the editor falls
    back to legacy highlighting.  Validate the query file as described
    above.

    Other possible causes:
    - In shared mode, the grammar's .so module is not installed in
      ~/.local/lib/mc/ts-grammars/ or $(libdir)/mc/ts-grammars/.
    - In static mode, the grammar was not included in
      --with-tree-sitter-grammars at configure time.
    - The filename does not match any pattern in the grammars config.
    - The grammar name in grammars does not match the function exported
      by the grammar module.
    - The .scm file is not found in the queries/ directory.

Colors look wrong:

    Check that the capture names in the query file match entries in the
    ts_default_colors[] table.  The lookup uses longest-prefix matching:
    @keyword.control is matched before @keyword.  If no prefix matches,
    the capture is ignored (default editor color is used).

A grammar causes high CPU usage or hangs:

    A 3-second parse timeout (ts_parser_set_timeout_micros) is set for
    all grammars as a safety net.  If a grammar consistently hits the
    timeout, consider disabling it by removing its entry from the
    grammars config file.

Build fails with "grammar sources not found":

    Grammar sources are normally downloaded automatically during
    configure.  If that failed, download manually:

        make -C src/editor/ts-grammars download-grammars

    For offline builds, point to a directory with pre-downloaded sources:

        TREE_SITTER_GRAMMARS_DIR=/path/to/grammars ./configure --with-tree-sitter

Build fails with type errors in grammar code:

    Grammars were generated by different tree-sitter versions.  The
    compatibility headers in src/editor/ts-grammars/tree_sitter/ handle
    most version mismatches.  If you encounter new errors after updating
    a grammar, you may need to:
    - Add new compatibility typedefs to tree_sitter/parser.h.
    - Add warning suppression flags to AM_CFLAGS in
      src/editor/ts-grammars/Makefile.in.

Build fails with undefined reference to tree_sitter_<name>:

    In static mode, ensure the grammar is listed in all_ts_grammars in
    configure.ac and has an entry in ts-grammar-registry.h.  In shared
    mode, ensure the .so module exports the expected symbol name (check
    with: nm -D mc-ts-<name>.so | grep tree_sitter).


Limitations
-----------

- Query files are all-or-nothing: if any node name is invalid, the
  entire query is rejected.  There is no partial fallback within a
  single query file.

- Languages without a pre-built parser.c (i.e. those requiring
  tree-sitter generate) are not supported.  Only grammars with
  committed parser.c files in their upstream repos are included.

- The color mapping is global.  Per-language color overrides are
  achieved by using more specific capture names in query files (e.g.
  @keyword.directive for Make), not by configuring colors per language.

- The highlight cache covers the viewport plus 8 KB.  Very long lines
  or extreme scroll speeds may cause brief flicker as the cache is
  rebuilt.

- Dynamic injection (inject_dynamic) relies on the language name
  in the source matching a registered grammar name exactly.  Common
  aliases (e.g. "py" for "python", "js" for "javascript") are not
  resolved automatically.
